+\section{Research Track: KAM-Caged Knot States}
+\label{sec:rt_kam_caged_knot_states}
+
+\paragraph{Status and objective.}
+\textbf{[RESEARCH TRACK / HIGH PRIORITY / NOT YET CANONICAL].}
+This section formulates a falsifiable stability programme for resolved SST
+vortex knots.  Its purpose is not to infer stability from visual toroidal
+symmetry, knot type, the golden ratio, or numerical longevity alone.  It asks
+whether a certified finite-core knot admits a relative equilibrium or periodic
+relative orbit whose reduced perturbation dynamics contain persistent
+quasi-periodic invariant tori.
+
+The central distinction is
+\begin{align}
+    \mathrm{KAM\mbox{-}S}
+    &:
+    \text{spatial invariant tori of vortex lines in a steady Euler field},
+    \\
+    \mathrm{KAM\mbox{-}T}
+    &:
+    \text{temporal invariant tori of perturbation modes of the knot shape}.
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_ST_split}
+\end{align}
+The first is supported by rigorous steady-Euler existence results; the second
+is the open SST particle-stability problem
+\cite{KhesinKuksinPeraltaSalas2014,EncisoPeraltaSalas2015}.
+
+\subsection{Classical nearly integrable structure}
+\label{subsec:rt_kam_classical_structure}
+
+For an \(N\)-degree-of-freedom Hamiltonian system, action--angle variables
+\((\mathbf I,\boldsymbol\theta)\in\mathcal D\times\mathbb T^N\) give the
+nearly integrable form
+\begin{equation}
+    H(\mathbf I,\boldsymbol\theta)
+    =
+    H_0(\mathbf I)
+    +
+    \varepsilon H_1(\mathbf I,\boldsymbol\theta).
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_hamiltonian_split}
+\end{equation}
+The Hamilton equations are
+\begin{align}
+    \dot{\mathbf I}
+    &=
+    -\varepsilon\,\partial_{\boldsymbol\theta}H_1,
+    \\
+    \dot{\boldsymbol\theta}
+    &=
+    \boldsymbol\omega(\mathbf I)
+    +
+    \varepsilon\,\partial_{\mathbf I}H_1,
+    \qquad
+    \boldsymbol\omega(\mathbf I)
+    :=
+    \partial_{\mathbf I}H_0.
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_hamilton_equations}
+\end{align}
+At \(\varepsilon=0\), the actions are constant and the angles advance
+linearly.  Expanding the perturbation,
+\begin{equation}
+    H_1(\mathbf I,\boldsymbol\theta)
+    =
+    \sum_{\mathbf k\in\mathbb Z^N}
+    H_{1,\mathbf k}(\mathbf I)
+    e^{i\mathbf k\cdot\boldsymbol\theta},
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_fourier_expansion}
+\end{equation}
+shows that resonant denominators are controlled by
+\(\mathbf k\cdot\boldsymbol\omega\).  A standard non-resonance condition is
+\begin{equation}
+    \left|
+    \mathbf k\cdot\boldsymbol\omega
+    \right|
+    \geq
+    \frac{\gamma}{\lVert\mathbf k\rVert^{\tau}},
+    \qquad
+    \mathbf k\in\mathbb Z^N\setminus\{\mathbf0\},
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_diophantine_condition}
+\end{equation}
+with \(\gamma>0\) and exponent \(\tau\) above the dimension-dependent lower
+bound.  A Kolmogorov nondegeneracy condition is
+\begin{equation}
+    \det
+    \left[
+    \frac{\partial^2H_0}{\partial I_j\partial I_k}
+    \right]
+    \neq0.
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_kolmogorov_nondegeneracy}
+\end{equation}
+Under the required analyticity or differentiability hypotheses and sufficiently
+small perturbation, a positive-measure Cantor family of non-resonant invariant
+tori persists \cite{Kolmogorov1954,Arnold1963KAM,Moser1962InvariantCurves}.
+
+\textbf{[GEOMETRIC GUARD].}
+The torus \(\mathbb T^N\) in Eqs.~\eqref{eq:rt_kam_hamiltonian_split}--
+\eqref{eq:rt_kam_kolmogorov_nondegeneracy} is generally a torus in phase
+space.  It must not be identified with the physical supporting torus of a
+torus knot without an explicit reduction that maps one structure to the
+other.
+
+\subsection{Spatial cage: invariant vortex-line tori}
+\label{subsec:rt_kam_spatial_cage}
+
+Let \(\mathbf v_0(\mathbf x)\) be a steady incompressible Euler field and
+\(\boldsymbol\omega_0=\nabla\times\mathbf v_0\).  Vortex lines satisfy
+\begin{equation}
+    \frac{d\mathbf x}{d\sigma}
+    =
+    \boldsymbol\omega_0(\mathbf x).
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_vortex_line_flow}
+\end{equation}
+In a thin invariant tube, local coordinates may be chosen so that the
+integrable reference field reads
+\begin{align}
+    \dot\theta_1&=\omega_1(I),
+    &
+    \dot\theta_2&=\omega_2(I),
+    &
+    \dot I&=0.
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_spatial_integrable_coordinates}
+\end{align}
+The rotation number is
+\begin{equation}
+    \nu(I)
+    =
+    \frac{\omega_1(I)}{\omega_2(I)},
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_spatial_rotation_number}
+\end{equation}
+and a two-frequency twist condition is
+\begin{equation}
+    \frac{d\nu}{dI}\neq0,
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_spatial_twist}
+\end{equation}
+or, equivalently where both frequencies are nonzero,
+\begin{equation}
+    \omega_1'(I)\omega_2(I)
+    -
+    \omega_1(I)\omega_2'(I)
+    \neq0.
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_spatial_wronskian_twist}
+\end{equation}
+
+\begin{definition}[Spatial KAM cage]
+A resolved vortex tube is \emph{spatially KAM-caged} on a specified steady
+background if it contains an elliptic periodic core vortex line surrounded by
+a positive-measure set of nested invariant tori with nonzero twist and
+Diophantine rotation numbers.
+\label{def:rt_spatial_kam_cage}
+\end{definition}
+
+Steady Euler constructions with arbitrarily prescribed knot and link type
+supply an orthodox existence precedent for this definition.  They include a
+positive-measure family of invariant tori and infinitely many periodic vortex
+lines after a sufficiently small smooth deformation of the prescribed tubes
+\cite{EncisoPeraltaSalas2015}.  This does not identify the resulting Beltrami
+field with an SST particle state, but it shows that a literal spatial
+transport cage is compatible with classical incompressible Euler dynamics.
+
+\subsection{Temporal cage: relative equilibrium before KAM}
+\label{subsec:rt_kam_temporal_cage}
+
+Let \(\mathbf X(s,t)\) be an arclength-resolved centreline and use a declared
+finite-core regularization \(a\).  A representative self-induced evolution is
+\begin{equation}
+    \partial_t\mathbf X(s,t)
+    =
+    \frac{\Gamma}{4\pi}
+    \operatorname{PV}\!\oint
+    \frac{
+    \partial_{s'}\mathbf X(s',t)
+    \times
+    [\mathbf X(s,t)-\mathbf X(s',t)]
+    }{
+    \left(
+    |\mathbf X(s,t)-\mathbf X(s',t)|^2+a^2
+    \right)^{3/2}
+    }
+    \,ds'.
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_regularized_biot_savart_evolution}
+\end{equation}
+The regularization, core profile, domain, and boundary correction are part of
+the model definition; Eq.~\eqref{eq:rt_kam_regularized_biot_savart_evolution}
+must not be mixed with an unregularized energy or with a different evolution
+kernel.
+
+A knot that retains its shape while translating and rotating is a relative
+equilibrium.  In a co-moving frame it obeys
+\begin{equation}
+    \mathbf v_{\rm BS}[\mathbf X_*](s)
+    =
+    \mathbf U
+    +
+    \boldsymbol\Omega\times\mathbf X_*(s)
+    +
+    \lambda(s)\partial_s\mathbf X_*(s),
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_relative_equilibrium_condition}
+\end{equation}
+where the tangential term changes parametrization but not the geometric curve.
+The objective residual is
+\begin{equation}
+    \mathcal R_{\rm RE}
+    :=
+    \min_{\mathbf U,\boldsymbol\Omega,\lambda}
+    \frac{
+    \left\lVert
+    \mathbf v_{\rm BS}
+    -\mathbf U
+    -\boldsymbol\Omega\times\mathbf X_*
+    -\lambda\partial_s\mathbf X_*
+    \right\rVert_{L^2}
+    }{
+    \max\!\left(
+    \lVert\mathbf v_{\rm BS}\rVert_{L^2},
+    v_{\rm floor}
+    \right)
+    }.
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_relative_equilibrium_residual}
+\end{equation}
+The floor \(v_{\rm floor}>0\) must be declared and scaled with the simulation
+units.  A standard KAM expansion is blocked until a configuration with a
+converged small \(\mathcal R_{\rm RE}\) is found.  Relative equilibria and
+shape-preserving vortex-filament motion are orthodox classical concepts
+\cite{Kida1981VortexFilamentForm}.
+
+\subsection{Local induction as the integrable reference layer}
+\label{subsec:rt_kam_lia_reference}
+
+For a slender filament, the logarithmically enhanced local contribution gives
+the local-induction equation
+\begin{equation}
+    \partial_t\mathbf X
+    =
+    \beta\kappa\mathbf b,
+    \qquad
+    \beta
+    =
+    \frac{\Gamma}{4\pi}\Lambda,
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_lia_equation}
+\end{equation}
+where \(\kappa\) is curvature, \(\mathbf b\) the Frenet binormal, and
+\(\Lambda\) a dimensionless slenderness logarithm with a core-profile-dependent
+finite term.  The corresponding leading energy is proportional to length,
+\begin{equation}
+    H_{\rm LIA}[\mathbf X]
+    =
+    T_{\Lambda}L[\mathbf X],
+    \qquad
+    T_{\Lambda}
+    =
+    \frac{\rhoF\Gamma^2}{4\pi}\Lambda.
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_lia_hamiltonian}
+\end{equation}
+Here \([T_{\Lambda}]=\mathrm{J\,m^{-1}}=\mathrm N\), so
+\([H_{\rm LIA}]=\mathrm J\).
+
+Under the Hasimoto transform
+\begin{equation}
+    \psi(s,t)
+    =
+    \kappa(s,t)
+    \exp\!\left[
+    i\int^s\tau(s',t)\,ds'
+    \right],
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_hasimoto_transform}
+\end{equation}
+Eq.~\eqref{eq:rt_kam_lia_equation} maps, after the conventional time scaling
+and phase gauge, to the focusing nonlinear Schr\"odinger equation
+\begin{equation}
+    i\psi_t+\psi_{ss}+\frac12|\psi|^2\psi=0.
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_focusing_nlse}
+\end{equation}
+This supplies an integrable reference system, not a proof that an arbitrary
+closed knotted filament is an exact LIA solution or remains closed after an
+arbitrary NLS reconstruction \cite{Hasimoto1972,JerrardSeis2017}.
+
+Using the canonical SST circulation
+\begin{equation}
+    \Gamma_0
+    =
+    2\pi\rc\vchar
+    =
+    9.68361920349\times10^{-9}\ \mathrm{m^2\,s^{-1}},
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_gamma_numeric}
+\end{equation}
+we obtain
+\begin{align}
+    \beta_0
+    &=
+    7.70597931627\times10^{-10}\,\Lambda
+    \ \mathrm{m^2\,s^{-1}},
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_beta_numeric}
+    \\
+    T_{\Lambda,0}
+    &=
+    5.22352385021\times10^{-24}\,\Lambda
+    \ \mathrm{N}.
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_line_tension_numeric}
+\end{align}
+The dimensions satisfy
+\([\beta_0\kappa]=\mathrm{m\,s^{-1}}\) and
+\([T_{\Lambda,0}L]=\mathrm J\).
+
+\subsection{Full Biot--Savart correction and the smallness gate}
+\label{subsec:rt_kam_biot_savart_perturbation}
+
+The candidate decomposition is
+\begin{equation}
+    H_{\rm BS}
+    =
+    H_{\rm LIA}
+    +
+    \varepsilon_{\rm NL}H_{\rm NL}.
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_lia_full_bs_decomposition}
+\end{equation}
+It is useful only if the perturbation is defined operationally.  Let
+\(\mathbb P_{\perp}\) remove the local tangential reparametrization direction,
+and let \(\mathbf v_{\rm rigid}\) be the least-squares translational and
+rotational velocity.  Define
+\begin{equation}
+    \varepsilon_{\rm NL}
+    :=
+    \frac{
+    \left\lVert
+    \mathbb P_{\perp}
+    \left(
+    \mathbf v_{\rm BS}
+    -\mathbf v_{\rm LIA}
+    -\mathbf v_{\rm rigid}
+    \right)
+    \right\rVert_{L^2}
+    }{
+    \max\!\left(
+    \lVert\mathbb P_{\perp}\mathbf v_{\rm LIA}\rVert_{L^2},
+    v_{\rm floor}
+    \right)
+    }.
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_nonlocality_ratio}
+\end{equation}
+The geometric slenderness diagnostics
+\begin{equation}
+    \epsilon_{\kappa}
+    =
+    a_{\rm core}\kappa_{\max},
+    \qquad
+    \epsilon_{\rm sep}
+    =
+    \frac{a_{\rm core}}{d_{\min}},
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_slenderness_diagnostics}
+\end{equation}
+are necessary metadata but are not substitutes for
+Eq.~\eqref{eq:rt_kam_nonlocality_ratio}.  In a knot, distant arclength
+segments can be spatially close, so a small local curvature ratio does not
+ensure a small nonlocal induction term.  Full Biot--Savart calculations show
+that winding data can contribute at leading order to vortex-knot motion
+\cite{ObertiRicca2019WindingDynamics}.
+
+\subsection{Symmetry reduction, Floquet gate, and normal form}
+\label{subsec:rt_kam_floquet_normal_form}
+
+Write a perturbation about the relative state as
+\begin{equation}
+    \mathbf X(s,t)
+    =
+    \mathbf X_*(s,t)
+    +
+    \boldsymbol\xi(s,t).
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_shape_perturbation}
+\end{equation}
+The linearized system is
+\begin{equation}
+    \partial_t\boldsymbol\xi
+    =
+    \mathcal L(t)\boldsymbol\xi.
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_linearized_shape_operator}
+\end{equation}
+For a periodic relative orbit with period \(T\), the monodromy operator is
+\begin{equation}
+    \mathcal M_T
+    =
+    \mathcal T
+    \exp\!\left[
+    \int_0^T\mathcal L(t)\,dt
+    \right].
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_monodromy_operator}
+\end{equation}
+After removing translation, rotation, arclength reparametrization, and global
+phase/time-shift modes, the nontrivial Floquet multipliers are
+\begin{equation}
+    \mu_j\in\operatorname{spec}(\mathcal M_T^{\rm red}).
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_reduced_floquet_multipliers}
+\end{equation}
+A necessary ellipticity gate is
+\begin{equation}
+    |\mu_j|=1
+    \qquad
+    \text{for every nontrivial retained mode}.
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_floquet_ellipticity_gate}
+\end{equation}
+Numerically, the deviation is reported as
+\begin{equation}
+    \rho_{\rm Fl}
+    :=
+    \max_j\left||\mu_j|-1\right|.
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_floquet_residual}
+\end{equation}
+Krein signatures must also be tracked: collision of unit-circle modes with
+opposite signature can generate a Hamiltonian instability even before a large
+geometric deformation is visible.
+
+On a finite, symmetry-reduced set of stable modes, the nonlinear normal form
+is written
+\begin{equation}
+    H_{\rm NF}
+    =
+    E_*
+    +
+    \sum_{j=1}^{N}\omega_j I_j
+    +
+    \frac12
+    \sum_{j,k=1}^{N}A_{jk}I_jI_k
+    +
+    R^{(3)}(\mathbf I,\boldsymbol\theta).
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_nonlinear_normal_form}
+\end{equation}
+The twist matrix is
+\begin{equation}
+    A_{jk}
+    =
+    \frac{\partial\omega_j}{\partial I_k}.
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_twist_matrix}
+\end{equation}
+The linear Hamiltonian \(\sum_j\omega_jI_j\) alone is Kolmogorov-degenerate;
+the nonlinear frequency shifts are therefore essential.  The reduced twist
+gate is
+\begin{equation}
+    \sigma_{\min}^{+}(A)
+    >
+    A_{\rm gate}>0,
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_twist_gate}
+\end{equation}
+where \(\sigma_{\min}^{+}\) excludes analytically identified null directions.
+No rank claim may include unremoved rigid-body or gauge modes.
+
+Toroidal vortex-filament models already demonstrate that energetic and
+dynamical stability are distinct and that different trefoil realizations can
+occupy different stability domains \cite{KolokolnikovTicknorKevrekidis2020}.
+This supports the gate sequence but does not substitute for full finite-core
+Euler or Biot--Savart certification.
+
+\subsection{Finite-order non-resonance and action drift}
+\label{subsec:rt_kam_nonresonance_drift}
+
+For a numerical mode truncation and a preregistered integer cutoff \(K\), define
+\begin{equation}
+    \Delta_{\gamma,\tau}^{(K)}
+    :=
+    \min_{\substack{
+    \mathbf k\in\mathbb Z^N\setminus\{\mathbf0\}\\
+    \lVert\mathbf k\rVert_1\leq K
+    }}
+    \lVert\mathbf k\rVert_1^{\tau}
+    \left|
+    \mathbf k\cdot\boldsymbol\omega
+    \right|.
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_finite_diophantine_margin}
+\end{equation}
+This is a finite-resolution diagnostic, not a proof of the infinite set of
+Diophantine inequalities.  It is useful for locating low-order resonances and
+for preregistering which combinations are excluded.
+
+For numerically reconstructed actions, define the normalized drift
+\begin{equation}
+    D_I(T)
+    :=
+    \max_j
+    \frac{
+    |I_j(T)-I_j(0)|
+    }{
+    T\max[I_j(0),I_{\rm floor}]
+    }.
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_action_drift}
+\end{equation}
+A KAM-like orbit requires bounded oscillatory action variation and no resolved
+secular drift over the declared observation window.  A small
+\(D_I\) over only a few turnover times is evidence of short-time regularity,
+not a KAM certificate.
+
+\subsection{Poincar\'e map and invariant-torus measure}
+\label{subsec:rt_kam_poincare_map}
+
+Choose a transverse section \(\Sigma\) and define the return map
+\begin{equation}
+    P:\Sigma\rightarrow\Sigma.
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_poincare_map}
+\end{equation}
+For an orbit with unwrapped angle \(\vartheta_n\), estimate the rotation number
+by
+\begin{equation}
+    \nu
+    =
+    \lim_{N\rightarrow\infty}
+    \frac{\vartheta_N-\vartheta_0}{2\pi N}.
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_numerical_rotation_number}
+\end{equation}
+The finite-window frequency drift is
+\begin{equation}
+    D_{\nu}
+    =
+    \frac{
+    |\nu_{[0,T/2]}-\nu_{[T/2,T]}|
+    }{T}.
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_frequency_drift}
+\end{equation}
+Let \(f_{\rm tor}\in[0,1]\) denote the fraction of the preregistered sampled
+section classified as invariant curves or invariant higher-dimensional tori by
+a resolution-converged classifier.  The exact classifier, sampling measure,
+and uncertainty must be reported.  Resonance islands, chaotic layers,
+cantori, and turnstile transport must not be merged into the same class
+\cite{MacKayMeissPercival1984}.
+
+\subsection{KAM certificate vector and promotion levels}
+\label{subsec:rt_kam_certificate}
+
+The proposed diagnostic vector is
+\begin{equation}
+    \boxed{
+    \mathcal C_{\rm KAM}
+    =
+    \left(
+    \mathcal R_{\rm RE},
+    \varepsilon_{\rm NL},
+    \rho_{\rm Fl},
+    \Delta_{\gamma,\tau}^{(K)},
+    \sigma_{\min}^{+}(A),
+    f_{\rm tor},
+    D_I,
+    \frac{d_{\min}}{a_{\rm core}}
+    \right).
+    }
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_certificate_vector}
+\end{equation}
+No scalar ``KAM score'' is canonical.  The full vector and its convergence
+sequence must remain visible because a good value in one component cannot
+compensate for failure of another.
+
+The certification ladder is
+\begin{center}
+\begin{tabularx}{0.94\textwidth}{@{}>{\bfseries}p{0.16\textwidth}X@{}}
+\toprule
+Level & Required result \\
+\midrule
+KAM--0 & Topology and finite thickness certified; no dynamical stability claim. \\
+KAM--1 & Converged relative equilibrium or periodic relative orbit with small \(\mathcal R_{\rm RE}\). \\
+KAM--2 & Reduced linearly elliptic spectrum with controlled Floquet residual and Krein audit. \\
+KAM--3 & Numerical invariant tori, nonzero twist, bounded drift, and positive \(f_{\rm tor}\). \\
+KAM--4 & Explicit nonlinear normal form with a quantitatively bounded remainder and verified finite-order non-resonance margins. \\
+KAM--5 & Computer-assisted a-posteriori KAM proof for the declared finite-dimensional map or rigorously justified reduction. \\
+\bottomrule
+\end{tabularx}
+\end{center}
+A KAM--5 result may be attempted through parameterization-method and interval
+arithmetic techniques that validate approximate invariant tori, Diophantine
+conditions, nondegeneracy, and analytic norm bounds
+\cite{FiguerasHaroLuque2017}.  It would certify the declared reduced map, not
+automatically the complete infinite-dimensional Euler equation.
+
+\subsection{Golden rotation-number null test}
+\label{subsec:rt_kam_golden_rotation_test}
+
+Define the golden number and its reciprocal by
+\begin{equation}
+    \phi
+    =
+    \frac{1+\sqrt5}{2},
+    \qquad
+    \nu_{\phi}
+    =
+    \phi^{-1}
+    =
+    [0;1,1,1,\ldots].
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_golden_rotation_number}
+\end{equation}
+Its continued-fraction convergents are Fibonacci ratios
+\begin{equation}
+    \frac{F_n}{F_{n+1}}
+    \longrightarrow
+    \nu_{\phi}.
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_fibonacci_convergents}
+\end{equation}
+This makes \(\nu_{\phi}\) a canonical example of a badly rationally
+approximable one-frequency rotation number.  In area-preserving twist maps,
+golden invariant curves are therefore standard breakup probes, often studied
+through periodic-orbit residues \cite{Greene1979StochasticTransition}.
+
+The SST hypothesis is deliberately weaker:
+\begin{equation}
+    \mathsf H_{\phi}:
+    \qquad
+    \varepsilon_{\rm break}(\nu_{\phi})
+    >
+    \operatorname{median}_{\nu\in\mathcal C}
+    \varepsilon_{\rm break}(\nu),
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_golden_break_hypothesis}
+\end{equation}
+for a preregistered control set \(\mathcal C\), after matching twist,
+amplitude, geometry, and numerical resolution.  Required controls include
+nearby rationals, at least one other noble irrational, and randomly selected
+irrationals.  The hypothesis is rejected if the preference disappears under
+those controls.  For systems with three or more independent frequencies, the
+relevant Diophantine object is a frequency vector; the scalar golden ratio has
+no automatic privileged status.
+
+\subsection{Golden logarithmic spiral: rejected centreline guard}
+\label{subsec:rt_kam_golden_spiral_guard}
+
+The logarithmic spiral
+\begin{equation}
+    r(\theta)
+    =
+    a e^{b\theta},
+    \qquad
+    b
+    =
+    \frac{2\ln\phi}{\pi}
+    =
+    0.306348962530\ldots
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_golden_log_spiral}
+\end{equation}
+satisfies
+\begin{equation}
+    r\!\left(\theta+\frac{\pi}{2}\right)
+    =
+    \phi r(\theta),
+    \qquad
+    r(\theta+2\pi)
+    =
+    \phi^4r(\theta).
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_golden_spiral_scaling}
+\end{equation}
+It is therefore open and scale-divergent.  It is rejected as the centreline of
+a closed SST particle carrier.  This rejection does not select a replacement
+geometry.  Any closed modulation family must first be compared against free
+Fourier, spline, and unmodulated controls and must pass topology, reach,
+clearance, relative-equilibrium, and stability gates before entering the
+release research track.
+
+\subsection{Geometry hierarchy and release-scope guard}
+\label{subsec:rt_kam_geometry_scope_guard}
+
+The recommended release hierarchy is
+\begin{equation}
+    \text{vortex ring}
+    \longrightarrow
+    3_1
+    \longrightarrow
+    4_1
+    \longrightarrow
+    \text{larger knot and link families only after single-knot certification}.
+    \label{eq:rt_kam_geometry_hierarchy}
+\end{equation}
+Specific composite links, product-phase architectures, modulo-class update
+rules, and preferred closed modulation families are intentionally outside the
+v0.8.25 release research track.  They may be recorded in a separately
+versioned non-release speculative appendix, but they may not influence the
+primary KAM optimizer, null tests, promotion levels, or Canon claims until
+independently promoted through the declared evidence gates.
+
+\subsection{Minimal numerical execution package}
+\label{subsec:rt_kam_numerical_package}
+
+The first implementation shall use the same centreline, regularization, and
+Biot--Savart operator in the equilibrium solve, tangent operator, and nonlinear
+evolution.
+
+\begin{enumerate}
+    \item \textbf{Geometry baseline.}
+    Start with the ring, then a uniformly arclength-resampled certified
+    trefoil.  Record \(L\), reach, \(\kappa_{\max}\), torsion statistics,
+    \(d_{\min}\), writhe, helicity metadata, topology certificate, and core
+    profile.
+
+    \item \textbf{Relative-state solve.}
+    Minimize Eq.~\eqref{eq:rt_kam_relative_equilibrium_residual} over admissible
+    geometry, translation, rotation, and tangential gauge.  Ropelength
+    optimality and dynamical relative equilibrium must be reported separately.
+
+    \item \textbf{Linear operator.}
+    Differentiate the same discrete evolution, project constraints and zero
+    modes, and compute the leading spectrum, Floquet multipliers, and Krein
+    signatures.  Validate matrix-free products against finite differences.
+
+    \item \textbf{Nonlinear frequency map.}
+    Excite each retained elliptic mode at several small amplitudes, reconstruct
+    \(I_j\), fit \(\omega_j(\mathbf I)\), and estimate the twist matrix of
+    Eq.~\eqref{eq:rt_kam_twist_matrix} with uncertainty and cross-validation.
+
+    \item \textbf{Poincar\'e and frequency-map analysis.}
+    Seed finite-core tracer surfaces, compute return maps, rotation numbers,
+    frequency drift, resonance islands, cantori, and radial transport.  Passive
+    tracers are disabled during equilibrium and eigensolver stages and restored
+    for this diagnostic stage.
+
+    \item \textbf{Perturbation continuation.}
+    Continue a declared perturbation family while measuring
+    \(\varepsilon_{\rm NL}\), \(\rho_{\rm Fl}\),
+    \(\Delta_{\gamma,\tau}^{(K)}\), \(f_{\rm tor}\), action drift, and
+    clearance.  Define the breakup event before inspecting the golden-ratio
+    result.
+
+    \item \textbf{Golden null test.}
+    Compare \(\nu_{\phi}\) with the preregistered control set at matched twist,
+    geometry, and action.  No golden constant may appear in the optimizer,
+    mesh, initial-condition selector, or stopping rule.
+
+    \item \textbf{Resolution sequence.}
+    Repeat across point count, quadrature order, timestep, core radius,
+    regularization family, domain size, and boundary treatment.  Report the
+    entire certificate vector in Eq.~\eqref{eq:rt_kam_certificate_vector} for
+    every level.
+\end{enumerate}
+
+\subsection{Preregistered falsifiers and promotion rule}
+\label{subsec:rt_kam_falsifiers}
+
+The KAM-caged knot hypothesis fails for a declared state if any of the
+following persists under refinement:
+\begin{enumerate}
+    \item no small-residual relative equilibrium or periodic relative orbit can
+    be obtained without changing the knot type or core model;
+    \item a nontrivial Floquet multiplier satisfies \(|\mu_j|>1+\delta_{\rm Fl}\)
+    with converged \(\delta_{\rm Fl}>0\);
+    \item the reduced twist matrix remains singular beyond known symmetry
+    directions;
+    \item the full-Biot--Savart correction is not perturbative in the tested
+    state, or the result changes qualitatively with the regularization;
+    \item invariant curves disappear under resolution refinement or are tracer
+    interpolation artefacts;
+    \item actions or rotation numbers exhibit secular drift incompatible with
+    the declared KAM level;
+    \item the tube loses clearance, reconnects, or changes isotopy class during
+    the measurement window;
+    \item the golden preference fails the preregistered null test.
+\end{enumerate}
+
+Promotion into the main canon requires at minimum KAM--3 for one vortex ring
+and one resolved trefoil under the same numerical protocol.  A theorem-level
+claim requires KAM--5 or a separate rigorous infinite-dimensional argument.
+Until then, ``KAM-caged SST particle'' denotes a research hypothesis and a
+certificate programme, not an established particle ontology.
+
+\paragraph{Child-level analogy.}
+The knot is like a train on a closed track.  Topology says the track remains
+knotted; Floquet analysis checks whether a small wobble grows; KAM analysis
+checks whether many small rhythms remain trapped on orderly lanes instead of
+combining into a destructive resonance.
+
+
